  "content_markdown": "Version: 8.3\nOn this page\nLevel: advanced\n**Unit testing** ([module testing](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Unit_testing)) is a software development process that lets you verify the operation capacity of isolated program components. Usually, developers write tests for each non-trivial method of a developed class. This lets you detect **source code regression** : errors in previously tested parts of the program.\nOne of the unit testing frameworks for .NET apps is [NUnit](http://nunit.org/), an open-source unit testing environment. A special **adapter** was developed to integrate NUnit with Visual Studio.\nYou can install the adapter in the following **ways** :\n* as Visual Studio extension\n* as NuGet project package that contains the implemented unit tests\nUse of the NUnit adapter **as a Visual Studio extension** has the following special features:\n* The adapter is available for any test project since the adapter becomes part of the IDE.\n* The extension is updated automatically.\n* Each team member who works on the test project must install a separate adapter.\nUse of the NUnit **as a NuGet package** has the following special features:\n* The package is a part of the Visual Studio project and available for all project developers.\n* The package must be installed for all unit test projects.\nLearn more about working with NUnit: [official vendor documentation](https://github.com/nunit/docs/wiki/NUnit-Documentation) (NUnit).\nTo **create unit tests** for user-made package class methods or properties:\n1. Install NUnit Visual Studio adapter.\n2. Turn on the [file system development mode](https://academy.creatio.com/documents?ver=8.3&id=15111&anchor=title-2098-3).\n3. Set up the unit test project.\n4. Create tests.\n5. Test the methods or properties.\n* * *\n## Resources\u200b\n[Module testing](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Unit_testing) (Wikipedia)\n[Official NUnit website](http://nunit.org/)\n[Official NUnit documentation](https://github.com/nunit/docs/wiki/NUnit-Documentation)",
